nIt seems I'm reflecting on string interpolation in JSON, particularly with the raw interpolated string literal. If I use something like `json\\\"\\\"\\\"\\\"greeting $name\\\"\\\"\\\"\\\"`, it encodes as a JSON string rather than concatenation. This raises questions: if the string contains both interpolation and adjacent literal text, would that make it invalid? I wonder if I should test the interpolation when it’s the entire string value in an object or array. Also, I'm curious about how duplicate object keys are handled in JSON.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring JSON number handling**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how existing implementations only count numbers without verifying them, but the public feature preserves decimal representations for JSON numbers. This may involve using `JsonNumber.fromString` for arbitrary precision, like BigDecimal and BigInt, yet it seems there's no test for standard numeric precision. I should note that key interpolation in objects is covered, but I wonder about compile-time errors with literals. Also, I'm curious how Option types are managed with encoders, especially for values like Some, None, and null.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing JSON interpolations**\\n\\nI’m looking into testing interpolations in JSON that contain UUID-like strings. The way replacement generates a random placeholder that isn't present in stringParts makes testing challenging. It seems this isn’t functional either. The idea of supporting user content that appears like placeholders isn’t really relevant here. I need to consider native compilation since tests compile in normal Scala while macros run at compile time. Perhaps I can add tests for interpolated field values in all JSON scalar positions, including Options, since we already have values at the root level.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating array structures**\\n\\nI'm considering whether there's already an existing array within the object. It seems there might not be a root object, but I don't have a root array directly accessible. However, I can construct root-level arrays that preserve ordering and mixed types. I see there are nested arrays, but no root array. Maybe it would be too duplicate? I might need to check the upstream tests for features related to this.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_kDe2mecZWHP8xwp3hU2YjnwX|fc_017f9dd791b5bcbd016a2a738d55888197a54f53fc7c67ede3", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request\nurls=[\n'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/circe/circe/v0.14.15/modules/literal/shared/src/test/scala-3/io/circe/literal/JsonLiteralSuite.scala',\n'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/circe/circe/v0.14.15/modules/literal/shared/src/test/scala/io/circe/literal/JsonLiteralSuite.scala',\n'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/circe/circe/v0.14.15/modules/literal/shared/src/test/scala/io/circe/literal/LiteralSuite.scala'\n]\nfor url in urls:\n try:\n  print('URL', url)\n  print(urllib.request.urlopen(url, timeout=10).read().decode()[:3000])\n except Exception as e:\n  print(type(e).__name__, e)\nPY", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 3102, "output": 791, "cacheRead": 16384, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 20277, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781166971267, "responseId": "resp_017f9dd791b5bcbd016a2a737bbafc8197946256fec32de505"}}
